@node "Intr" "Introduction"
This  will allow a user to download directory listings from their
current conference. Difference between this and  other  doors  is
that  it  will  send  the  user renamed files. It won't just send
'DIR1' text file. It'll be called 'XPressSupport1' or whatever.
@endnode
@node "spec" "Specifications"
Mo-Email is currently running on my:  A1200/020/882
                                      10 Meg RAM
                                      85 Meg Drive
                                      /X version 4.#?
@endnode
@node "Impo" "Important!"
MoDown gleans all its information from your  current  BBS  icons.
First  it  will check out what conference the user is in. If he's
in conference 2 then the script will check out the icon for  that
particular conference. IE: (My BBS setup...)

User in    > 2:Express Support
Real name  > BBS:Conf2
Checks     > BBS:Conf2.info

...and finds the 'NDIRS=' tooltype. It it doesn't exist then  the
program  exits.  If  it has '0' the program will exit. I've tried
to think up all fuckhead results from checking this tooltype  and
believe everything is covered.

User  can then choose which directory listing to download. It can
be a single listing or all. Whatever it is it will be  copied  to
'T:MoDown(user's-node)/'  -  all  dir  listings  renamed  to  the
current conference  name  (stripped  of  spaces  and  other  misc
characters) + original dir listing number.

User  then  chooses  download options. If he chose (ALL) then the
program will fail to activate the packer option '(4)-NONE'.  This
only works for a single listing download.

If  a  packer  is  chosen then the user waits until it's done its
thang, then 'hit a key' to download. As  directory  listings  are
all  copied  to  'T:etc...'  the  system  will appear to be doing
nothing, but it is packing.

(In Built Stealth Mode Function ® sAFRA 1972)

But seriously, I have seen another door like  this  on  an  alien
BBS  system  that  let the user see the status of the packing. As
if the LHA etc output was piped to the AmiExpress  screen.  Well,
I  know  little  of  this,  and PIPE, don't know what I'm talking
about, so if anyone DOES...lemme know.

Remember: BETA Tester!

@endnode
